<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Calls for Lifting of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) Sunday called for lifting of the U.N. sanctions on Iraq,
which were imposed after Iraqi troops stormed into Kuwait in
August 1990.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions must come to an end because they are only
worsening the plight of the Iraqi people while the Iraqi
government is not affected, UAE Minister of Information and
Culture Sheikh Abdullah Bin Zayed Al Nahyan said in an interview
here with the Jordian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, the continuing of sanctions will have an adverse
effect on the U.S. credibility as a peace sponsor," Sheikh
Abdullah added.
</P>
<P>
On the peace negotiations between the Palestinians and Israel,
the minister said that the main issues are still pending.
</P>
<P>
"The task will not be that easy. I do not think that the
Palestinians have anything left to concede," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the Israelis will never negotiate on main issues
like the status of Jerusalem and the return of Palestinian
refugees without guaranteeing further Palestinian concessions.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Abdullah also expressed his confidence in the the UAE
federation, which was composed of Abu Dhabi, Dubai, Sharjah, Ras
Al Khaimah, Fujairah, Umm Al Qaiwain and Ajman.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he was worried about the future of the federation,
which was founded in 1971, he said that the federation is
coherent and sound.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot imagine that even a single citizen has doubt about
the future of the federation. This question could have been asked
ten years ago, not now," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
