<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Multilateral Talks Before Syrian-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Sunday that the multilateral peace talks will not
be resumed before Israel restarts negotiations with Syria and
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the multilateral talks should follow that of
the peace negotiations on all tracks, including the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks, Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The multilateral talks, which kicked off in 1992, came to a
halt in 1996 when former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
took power. The negotiations covered issues including disarmament,
water, Palestinian refugees, the environment and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has agreed to implement the
peace deals with the Palestinians and has started the negotiations
with the Palestinians for a final peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Barak has also promised to resume the stalled talks with Syria
and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks were suspended in early 1996 due
to disputes over the Golan Heights which Israel seized from Syria
in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel in 1979, but bilateral relations were cool during the
hard-line Netanyahu's period in office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
