<HEADLINE> U.S. Not to Change Policy Towards S. Africa: Mbeki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Should the Republicans
come into power in the United States next year, there will be no
change in policy towards South Africa, South African President
Thabo Mbeki predicted.
</P>
<P>
"(South Africa's) relations with the U.S. government are very
good. In fact, they're excellent," Mbeki said in a pre-recorded
interview broadcast Sunday by South African Broadcasting
Corporation (SABC) television.
</P>
<P>
The South African president said he believed that if there was
a change in the U.S. administration from Democratic to Republican,
he didn't think there would be much of a change in policy.
</P>
<P>
"There had always been a bipartisan approach towards South
Africa in the United States," said Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
"Even in the apartheid years there was a great insistence --
correctly -- on a bipartisan approach with regard to South
Africa," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said he was prepared to meet the Republican's front
runner for presidential candidate, Texas governor, George Bush.
</P>
<P>
He had wanted to pay a courtesy call on junior Bush during his
recent trip to the United States, but the governor's hectic
schedule had not allowed for this.
</P>
<P>
However, Mbeki said he would still meet the governor.
</P>
<P>
"I will see him. He is, so it seems, a leading candidate for
the presidency of the Republican side."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki dismissed reports that he had cancelled his visit to
Texas because he did not wish to embarrass U.S. Vice-President Al
Gore, the likely Democratic Party nominee.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki and Gore share a special relationship having chaired the
U.S.- South Africa bi-national commission under the Nelson Mandela
and Bill Clinton administrations.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, when President Clinton became Democratic candidate...
we actually saw him, before he became president," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would like Deputy President Jacob Zuma as his
successor as co- chair of the commission with Gore, even though
the U.S. vice-president wanted the status quo to remain.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also dismissed reports that he had snubbed President
Clinton by refusing to share a limousine with him after bilateral
talks earlier this week in New York.
</P>
<P>
"I saw the story and it made me feel a little bit sad. I don't
know why anybody would want to invent a story," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
