<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coalition Crisis Resolved in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A weeks-long coalition
crisis in Israel was resolved Sunday after an agreement was
reached over the governmental funding of religious schools
belonging to the powerful ultra-Orthodox party Shas.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between the Education Ministry and the Shas
party will pave way for thousands of teachers in Shas' schools to
get their salaries, unpaid for more than three months, as soon as
Monday, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Shas issued its threat to quit the coalition of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak if the government would not transfer 12
million shekels (about 2.85 million U.S. dollars) to its
educational network.
</P>
<P>
Finance and Education officials, however, insisted that Shas
had to formulate a reform plan before the transfer of money could
be made, citing reports that millions of shekels had been wasted
due to mismanagement and alleged corruption.
</P>
<P>
Shas, the third largest party in the parliament, controls 17 of
68 seats in Barak's coalition, which had 73 seats before another
ultra-religious party, the United Torah Judaism, withdrew its five
members early this month in protest against Barak's consent to
transport heavy power equipment on the Jewish weekend Shabbath.
</P>
<P>
Religious institutes enjoyed preferential treatment in the
three years of rule of former right-wing prime minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, raising resentment among the secular public.
</P>
<P>
In the campaign leading to his election victory in May, Barak
pledged to change the national priorities and stop the overflow of
money to the religious schools and institutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
