<HEADLINE> Southern African Countries Urged To Unite On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Vice-President
Simon Muzenda Sunday urged the southern African countries to make
collective decisions on security to avoid manipulation by
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
"Outside powers cannot manipulate us as a collective unit but
can easily do that to individual countries," Muzenda said at a
Southern African Regional Institute for Policy Studies 1999 annual
colloquium in Harare.
</P>
<P>
"Decisions on security matters have to be made through mutual
consultation,!1he said.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda pointed out that it was the policy of some big powers
to project their power through operating in designated regional
centers of influence.
</P>
<P>
It was time Africa started resolving its conflicts by
themselves, he noted, saying that the United Nations had failed to
intervene in conflict areas where Africa had wanted it to act.
</P>
<P>
He said the Organization of African Unity (OAU) should take a
lesson from U.N.'s stance on conflicts from situations in Rwanda,
Somalia and the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
"The conflicts have convinced Africa to take a more active role
in the resolution to African conflicts. The OAU must champion
this cause," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean vice-president said that anti-government rebels
in southern Africa like the National Union for Total Independence
in Angola (UNITA) should seek civilized ways of participating in
the political and economic development of their countries.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, he said, the end of the cold war led to the
increase of conflicts in various parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Africa had also taken a share of the conflicts, contributing to
the slowing down of the development process in the continent, said
Muzenda.
</P>
<P>
"The end of the cold war created optimism as high expectations
about peace throughout the world. Unfortunately, this has not
been the case," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Civil wars and inter-state conflicts have actually increased
in various parts of the world," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
