<HEADLINE> Iraqi Civilian Targets Bombed by U.S.-British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Civilian facilities in the
southern Iraqi province of Basra were bombed on Saturday evening
by the United States and British warplanes, an Iraqi military
spokesman announced on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 20:50 local time (1650 GMT), 22
formations of U.S. and British warplanes coming from Saudi and
Kuwaiti bases violated southern Iraqi airspace over the provinces
of Basra, Thi-Qar, Muthana, Najaf and Qadisiyah.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes bombed some civilian and service facilities in
Basra, said the spokesman. He did not mention whether casualties
were inflicted or not.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back at the U.S. and British
planes and forced them to flee to their bases, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nine formations of U.S. and British warplanes coming from
Turkish airspace violated northern Iraqi airspace over Neineva,
Erbil and Dohuk provinces at 12:05 local time (0805 GMT) on
Sunday, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's massive airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have made 12,857 sorties over the two no-fly
zones in Iraq, and have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian
and military targets, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led western
allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from possible attacks by Iraqi government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
