<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of CPC Central Committee Decision (17) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seven. Improving Balance of SOE Debts and
</P>
<P>
 Assets and Reducing SOE Social Burdens
</P>
<P>
It is of utmost importance in effecting the SOE reform and
development to gradually solve problems of the SOEs such as too
high asset-to-liability rate, capital shortage and heavy social
burdens. These problems should be solved step-by-step through
various means according to the current macro-economic environment
and the State financial power.
</P>
<P>
(1) Chinese banks should increase reserves for writing off the
bad loans caused by acquisition and bankruptcy of big and medium-
sized SOEs and closure of the mines whose resources have dried up,
and for supporting key industries. State-owned and collectively-
owned enterprises may enjoy relevant encouraging policies while
acquiring SOEs. All the employees displaced by acquired, bankrupt
and closed enterprises should be settled well in line with
relevant State regulations.
</P>
<P>
(2) Major SOEs, those currently debt-ridden but have market for
some of their products and have prospects for development, should
solve the problem of high asset-to-liability rate by debt-to-
equity transformation, together with the State banks' current
reform on handling non-performing loans. Enterprises which adopt
the reform of debt-to-equity should change their current operating
mechanism and execute standard company system, and their
performance will later be independently appraised by financial and
asset management firms. All this must be done in accordance with
the rule of the market economy and related rules and regulations
to avoid possible losses of State assets.
</P>
<P>
(3) Direct fund raising should be increased. SOEs which already
meet the qualifications for listing may raise funds in domestic
and overseas capital markets, and the proportion of public shares
under current circulation should appropriately be increased. Other
SOEs may prepare for the listing by debt reshuffling. State-owned
and share-holding enterprises are allowed to participate in the
allocation of new shares according to relevant regulations. A
number of promising enterprises with good credibility will be
picked out to reduce the State shares provided this will not
affect the State control of shares. The State will use the surplus
capital for SOE reform and development. The system of stock
issuance and listing should be further improved to promote the
healthy development of the securities market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of CPC Central Committee Decision (20) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Preferential policies should be improved to facilitate the re-
employment of displaced workers, encouraging them to get re-
employed as soon as possible by accepting jobs in non-public
entities, starting their own business or becoming self-employed.
</P>
<P>
As for those who start their own businesses, the government
should grant them more support in getting official permits,
finding office sites, enjoying reduced or exempted taxes, and
receiving bank loans. The labor market should be actively
developed and regulated so as a market-oriented employment
mechanism could be formed.
</P>
<P>
Speeding up the building of the social security system is an
important prerequisite for a smooth implementation of the State-
owned enterprise reform. The social security services such as
endowment, unemployment and medical insurance should cover people
of a wider range, and State-owned township enterprises,
collectively-owned enterprises, overseas-funded ventures and
private businesses and their employees should all take part in the
social security program, and hand in insurance premium.
</P>
<P>
The collection of social insurance premium should be stepped up,
and measures should be taken to collect the defaulted premiums to
ensure a timely and full payment of the retirement pensions. A
unified management plan of retirement pension funds at the
province-level should be further improved, and multiple measures
such as selling off some State assets and readjusting the fiscal
spending structure should be taken to expand new fund-raising
channels for social security program and replenish the social
security funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
