<HEADLINE> Malaysian Firm to Invest $6Bln in Ethiopia's Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A Malaysian company has
signed a six-billion-U.S. dollar project agreement with Ethiopia
in a bid to speed up constructions in the rural areas of the Horn
of africa country.
</P>
<P>
Adorna Shebele Company of Malaysia would mainly invest in
Ethiopia's urbanization projects including the construction of
200,000 residential houses, the Capital weekly reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed with the Addis Ababa City Council,
the Malaysian company will also invest in the modernization of the
Merkato market, which is the largest market in capital Addis
Ababa.
</P>
<P>
Adorna Shebele is one of the Adorna Investment Group of
Companies in Malaysia. The group is engaged in jewellery, real
estate development, education, tourism, trade and industry in
China and Australia.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian Investment Authority, the Malaysian
company also desires to invest in Ethiopia's railway construction,
agro-industry, agricultural development and tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
