<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Works to Eliminate Child Labor: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior Egyptian official said
on Sunday that his country spares no effort to eliminate child
labor.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is keen on removing the causes, primarily poverty and
illiteracy, of child labor, said Abdel Kader el Aasar, advisor for
international cooperation to the minister of insurance and social
affairs.
</P>
<P>
El Aasar made the remarks before leaving for Geneva to attend
meetings of an experts committee of the International Labor
Organization (ILO) on eliminating child labour.
</P>
<P>
Children in Egypt work in basic crafts and occupations, unlike
in some other countries where they are forced to involve in
unethical practices including drug-trafficking and sometimes war,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the population in Egypt are living under the
poverty line and child labor is not rare. However, the Egyptian
official said child labor was not a serious phenomenon in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian delegation will present a working paper to the ILO
meeting on Egypt's stance on agreements banning child labour, El
Aasar said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
