<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh PM Utilizes Her Peace Prize Money to Set International Prize Named After Her Father </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina on Sunday announced that she would introduce an
international prize named after "Father of the Nation Bangabandhu
Sheikh Mujibur Rahman" for peace and development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a mass reception accorded to her at the Paltan
Maidan in the capital city on her receiving the UNESCO Peace Prize
in Paris on Friday, Hasina said she would utilize the prize money
by setting up the foundation for an international prize named
after her father, the first prime minister of independent
Bangladesh who was assassinated in August 1975.
</P>
<P>
The reception was organized by the ruling Awami League.
</P>
<P>
Hasina and former U.S. senator George J. Mitchell jointly
received the 1998 UNESCO Peace Prize worth 800,000 franc (about
512,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Referring to the background that led to the conclusion of the
Chittagong peace accord in December 1997, Hasina said: "We always
considered it as a political problem and wanted to solve it
politically through discussions and negotiations."
</P>
<P>
She described the task of restoring peace in the Chittagong
Hill Tracts as a difficult one, saying that "any problem can be
solved if it is handled with sincerity and honesty."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said she had a vision to develop the country
by the year 2020 so that it could keep its head high in the
community of nations. "The county... will be able to achieve
progress and prosperity at any cost," she said.
</P>
<P>
Congratulating the prime minister on receiving the peace award,
General Secretary of the ruling Awami League (AL) and Minister for
Local Government, Rural Development and Cooperatives Zillur Rahman
said that at least 35,000 people were killed in the country's
southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts over two decades of time.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister restored peace there through signing the
peace agreement with the tribal people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people attended the reception, carrying banners,
placards, miniature flags and colorful ribbons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
