<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Government to Tax Enterprises Laying Off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The French government will tax
those enterprises who are laying off workers while making profits,
after the Michelin tire group said it would lay off 10 percent of
its work force in Europe.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin is expected to announce
next week a series of measures against the enterprises who are
kicking off workers and those who employ a large percent of
workers on short-term contracts.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Solidarity and Employment Martine Aubry said
that those enterprises who are laying off workers should pay for
their acts.
</P>
<P>
The government could increase the tax subsidized for creating
jobs on those enterprises, while decreasing charges on those who
are keeping their workers, she said.
</P>
<P>
The government will also tax enterprises which employ more than
10 percent of their work force as short-term contract workers, she
added.
</P>
<P>
France has been greatly inspired by the recent agreement
reached by the U.S. auto workers' union UAW and the
DaimlerChrysler auto group on guaranteeing life employment for the
eldest workers.
</P>
<P>
The French Communist Party, which is part of the leftwing
coalition, has been increasing pressure on the Socialist-led
government to take measures against layoffs.
</P>
<P>
The Communists will organize a nationwide demonstration on
October 16 against layoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
