<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Founding Father Seriously Ill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian founding
father Julius Nyerere is seriously ill, President Benjamin Mkapa
confirmed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who called for a press conference at the State House in
Dar es Salaam, said that Nyerere, 77, is suffering from chronic
lymphocytic leukemia, or blood cancer, at St. Thomas Hospital in
London.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa made a stopover in London on Saturday morning after
concluding a 12-day working visit to the United States. He visited
Nyerere at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
An aide of Mkapa later told Xinhua, "Nyerere was a bit
conscious, but he could not speak."
</P>
<P>
"It (the disease attack) is coming and going," the aide said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa called for the press conference hours after he returned
to the capital Dar es Salaam en route Zurich, Switzerland. The
press conference is apparently aimed at dismissing rumors that
have been abounding these days in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa assured people in the country that Nyerere is getting
good treatment and he asked the nation to pray for the first
president of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who led his country to independence in 1961, was sent
to Britain weeks ago for a medical check-up, but was formally
admitted to the hospital later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
