<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dialog Urged In Zimbabwe to Avoid Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Both employers and employees
in Zimbabwe have been urged to hold dialog to avoid unnecessary
strikes which damage the economy of the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Industrial Relations Association made the call
Sunday, expressing concern over the spate of strikes in the
country which seem to suggest that the labor dispute settlement
process is not working.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the association, Lovemore Madhuku, said that
strikes, no matter how justifiable, should not last for days or
weeks as this hurt the economy.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the existing legal framework which
identified strikes as illegal was harmful to labor relations,
called for complete overhaul of the Labor Relations Tribunal as it
had a large backlog of cases resulting in matters going for weeks
without being resolved.
</P>
<P>
This discouraged the dialog between employers and employees
with employers banking on fire striking employees, Madhuku said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the employers should change their attitudes so as
to improve dialog rather than be quick to fire striking employees.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government should entrench the right to
strike but there should be a clear mechanism to break the strike.
</P>
<P>
This could be achieved through compulsory arbitration, where
matters could be resolved urgently.
</P>
<P>
Only this month Zimbabwe recorded more than four strikes, with
the hotel and catering industry strike dragging for more than a
week.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the health service was paralyzed after junior doctors
went on strike demanding pay and allowance increments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
