<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian voters cast their ballots on Sunday in a
referendum certain to endorse parliament nomination of President
Hosni Mubarak for a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
The poll started at 8:00 local time (0500 GMT) and will end at
17:00 (1400 GMT). Results are expected on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was first elected president in 1981 after the
assassination of former president Anwar Sadat. He was re-elected
twice in 1987 and 1993. In the past referendums, Mubarak received
more than 95 percent "yes" votes.
(BC-Egypt-Referendum-Mubarak)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Qatar's Supreme Criminal Court on Sunday began
the trial of Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassem Bin Hamad Al-Thani, the
suspected mastermind of a 1996 coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
Two other suspects, who were identified as Ghanem Saleh
Al-Kawari and Mete'b Twaim Al-Meri, were also brought to the
court.
</P>
<P>
The public prosecutor charged the three with attempting to oust
Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani in collaboration with a
foreign country and to leak state military secrets.
(BC-Qatar-Coup-Trial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The new housing construction tenders for
settlement expansion in the Israeli-occupied Arab territories
will seriously jeopardize the peace process with the Palestinians
and Syrians, said an Israeli peace group here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
After learning that Israeli Housing and Construction Ministry
has issued tenders for building 2,600 new houses for Jewish
settlers in West Bank settlements, the Peace Now group said this
action will cause more trouble for the Israeli-Palestinian
final-status talks (BC-Israel-Settlement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A weeks-long coalition crisis in Israel was
resolved Sunday after an agreement was reached over the
governmental funding of religious schools belonging to the
powerful ultra-Orthodox party Shas.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between the Education Ministry and the Shas
party will pave way for thousands of teachers in Shas' schools to
get their salaries, unpaid for more than three months, as soon as
Monday, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Shas issued its threat to quit the coalition of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak if the government would not transfer 12
million shekels (about 2.85 million U.S. dollars) to its
educational network. (BC-Israel-Coalition) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Reform of International Monetary System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- China called here Sunday
for reform of the current international monetary and financial
system to accommodate the needs of international economic and
financial development.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, Governor of the People's Bank of China, said the
role of international reserve currency played by a few countries'
national currency has been a major source of instability in the
international monetary system.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at 53rd meeting of the Interim Committee of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), Dai said the fluctuation in
exchange rates increases uncertainty in trade and investment and
exposure to speculative transactions, and generates different
types of derivatives resulting in the popularity of highly
leveraged operations.
</P>
<P>
Huge risks abound on the international financial market, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Dai pointed out that the current international financial system
cannot solve the balance of payments imbalance, which has
repeatedly been the cause of international financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong called on the international community to consider
the additional allocation of SDRs and create conditions to
increase their use and strengthen the Fund's function of providing
liquidity to its member countries to solve the problem of an
international reserve currency.
</P>
<P>
Dai also urged the major industrial countries to shoulder the
responsibility in coordinating their policies effectively to
establish a new exchange rate mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong stressed that in reforming the international
financial system, the developing countries should be more involved
in the process and should not be forced to restructure their
economies according to the developed countries' standards.
</P>
<P>
"The operations of the international monetary system and its
reforms should not be controlled by a few member countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Dai said if the developed countries' could not pay enough
attention to the level of economic development in the developing
countries and solely call on these countries for opening markets,
the developing countries may encounter new crisis.
</P>
<P>
On the role of IMF and its reforms, Dai Xianglong said the IMF
has always been at the core of the international monetary systems
and its functions are irreplaceable.
</P>
<P>
However, the Fund needs to reflect on its experiences and
lessons, improve its efficiency, pursue substantive reform, and
continue to enforce cooperation with other international
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Dai expressed his support for the proposal to change the name
of the Interim Committee into "International Monetary and
Financial Committee".
</P>
<P>
Full account should be taken of the representativeness and
effectiveness in the process of reforming the Interim Committee,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Sufficient attention should be paid to ensure that the
representation of the developing countries is enhanced and that
their voice is heard, he added.
</P>
<P>
On Chinese economic growth and reform, Dai Xianglong said in
1999, the Chinese government has continued its vigorous and active
fiscal policy, appropriate monetary policy, and maintained steady
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He said in 1999, GDP is expected to increase by at least 7
percent, and the RMB exchange rate will remain stable.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the Chinese economy will continue to grow in the
context of the deepening reform of the financial sector and
corporate restructuring," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (DAR) withstood the
challenge stemming from the financial crisis in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's GDP turned to positive growth in the second quarter
of 1999 and the region has passed its hard time, Dai said.
</P>
<P>
Dai said Hong Kong's appropriate policy measures have enabled
it to successfully weather the external shocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
