<HEADLINE> Britain on Way towards Long-Term Economic Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, Britain, September 27 (Xinhua) -- British
Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown, addressing the Labour
Party's annual conference on Monday, said the Government has been
successful in its efforts to rebuild long-term economic stability.
</P>
<P>
The essential stage of the Labour Government's journey since
the 1997 election has been to end "damaging economic instability,"
and to tackle the "boom and bust" which served the interests of
the privileged few but left millions insecure and worse off, Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
The Government has been pursuing "the values of economic
responsibility, planning for the long term, building stability
from solid foundations," in place of short-termism,
"take-what-you-can" attitudes and selfish irresponsibility,
according to Brown.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he said, Britain at the moment has mortgage rates
around their lowest levels for 20 years, inflation at its lowest
level in over 30 years, long-term interest rates at their lowest
levels in nearly 40 years and over 648,000 more jobs created.
</P>
<P>
"We will never return to the days of Tory (Conservative) boom
and bust," he asserted. "Labour Government will never take risks
with inflation. I will never let deficit get out of control. We
will not spend money we have not earned. Our years of
responsibility in Government have only just begun."
</P>
<P>
On the Labour Government's policy on the euro, Brown said "we
will be the party of Britain in Europe."
</P>
<P>
"Europe is where we are, where we trade, from where thousands
of businesses and millions of jobs come," he said, noting that a
successful Single Currency that meets Britain's "five economic
tests" is in the country's national economic interest.
</P>
<P>
Urging the business circles to embrace technological
revolution, Brown said economy of the next decade will need more
competition, more entrepreneurship, more flexibility and more
long-term investment.
</P>
<P>
"We must never again become a Party that is seen as
anti-success, anti-competition, anti-profit, anti-markets" he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
