<HEADLINE> Pinochet Extradition Hearing Opens in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The much-delayed hearing on
whether former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet should be
extradited to face trial in Spain started Monday in a crowded
British courtroom.
</P>
<P>
The elderly Pinochet did not attend the hearing, which is
expected to last five days.
</P>
<P>
He will have to be present when the verdict is made, which is
not expected until about two weeks after the extradition hearing
ends.
</P>
<P>
Police kept supporters and opponents of the former leader apart
as proceedings got underway at Bow Street Magistrates' Court in
London.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet is wanted by Spain for a string of alleged human
rights crimes during his 1973-90 rule.
</P>
<P>
The 83-year-old general was arrested in Britain on October 16,
1998, while convalescing from back surgery at a London clinic. He
has been fighting extradition ever since.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet will face around 36 charges, mainly allegations of
torture, which will be detailed in the opening session. They are
the result of an investigation by a Spanish judge, Baltasar Garzon.
</P>
</TEXT>
