<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Planning Helps Relieve Resource Shortages in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Family planning has helped
China relieve resource shortages and improve environmental
protection, according to the results of a recent survey conducted
by the State Family Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Three hundred million fewer people were born in China during
the past three decades than would have been without the family
planning policy, helping to relieve contradictions between rapid
population growth and environmental protection, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Since the implementation of the family planning policy in the
early 1980s, the per-capita grain output in China has increased
from 293 kilograms to 402 kilograms. Without the family planning
policy, the per-capita grain output could not have been expected
to increase at all, and China would face serious food shortages.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that the per-capita arable land in China has
dropped from about 0.1 hectare in 1978 to 0.08 hectare in 1997.
Without any control on population growth, that figure would have
been 0.06 hectare in 1997, worsening the shortage of arable land.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita water resources in China was 2,275 cubic meters in
1997, which indicates that China is already a country with a water
shortage. Without family planning, the per-capita water resource
would have been 1,836 cubic meters in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Family planning has also helped slow down the reduction in per-
capita forest area and the per-capita consumption of coal, iron,
phosphorus, potassium, salt and other resources, according to the
survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Nations Urged to Develop Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Africa should stop being a
provider of raw and unprocessed materials if it has to get a share
of the global market in the next millennium, Zambian Minister of
Commerce, Trade and Industry, David Mpamba, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba made the remarks when he opened the Third Meeting of the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) Committee
in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Dependence on the export of raw materials will create untold
poverty on this continent, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to develop industries that have the
capacity to turn Africa into the bread basket of the world.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba urged manufacturers in the region not to worry about the
 implications that are going to be brought about by a free trade
area.
</P>
<P>
He said the free trade area would create larger markets that
would enable the region to attract more investors.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba noted that currently national markets are too small to
allow firms to expand sufficiently and achieve the optimum scale
production.
</P>
<P>
COMESA Acting Secretary General Sindiso Ngwenya said COMESA
Free Trade Area (FTA), which was scheduled for October 31, 2000,
would enable firms not only to supply the regional market but also
the international market.
</P>
<P>
Ngwenya said the COMESA Economic Integration arrangement
spanning a period of 16 years has witnessed the gradual reduction
of customs duties to an extent that the average tariffs now stands
at two percent.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, conventional non-tariff barriers have
been eliminated through a combination of the COMESA programs and
the unilateral trade liberalization programs being pursued by
member states.
</P>
<P>
He told the meeting that about 50 billion U.S. dollars will be
required in the next five years to finance programs aimed at
enhancing trade and investment within the 21-member grouping.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the market size, he said, the average size of a
COMESA economy is about six billion dollars. In this regard, the
FTA will create a single economic space with a combined population
of approximately 380 million people and a combined Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) of 170 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
