<HEADLINE> Ugandans Urged to Promote Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Ugandans have been urged to
preserve traditional heritage in order to develop and to
revitalize the country's young tourism industry after a heavy
blow in March.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Second Deputy Prime Minister and Minister
of Tourism, Trade and Industry Moses Ali in a message addressed
to the general public here on the World Tourism Day, Radio Uganda
reported.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has rich tourist resources like wetlands, forest parks
and well- preserved bird species, the senior official said in the
message.
</P>
<P>
Preservation of cultural heritage is the first step to help
the country' s tourism to gain momentum in the coming century.
Uganda has to improve its image in the world's tourism stage, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Bwindi National Forest Park, which accounts for some 70
percent of the country's tourism revenue, was dealt a heavy blow
in early March when eight foreign tourists were hatched to death
by Rwandan Hutu extremists coming from the Democratic Republic of
the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The incident sparked a spate of mass tourist cancellations and
greatly dented the country's image in the international stage.
Although the government has done a lot to rekindle the stagnating
industry, still very few foreign tourists listed Uganda as their
tourist destination.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
