<HEADLINE> UN Kicks Off Special Session on Small Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
General Assembly on Monday kicked off special session on small
islands in which trade and environment will top the agenda.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, Some forty small islands nations
will use this opportunity to seek international support on trade
and environment problems.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. special session will assess progress on the action
plan adopted by over 100 countries five years ago at the 1994
Global Conference on the Sustainable Development of Small Island
Developing States.
</P>
<P>
While island nations often conjure up images of "paradise,"
their coasts, coral reefs and forests are under increasing stress
from pollution, development, climate and natural disaster, the
problems often beyond their means or control to solve.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and President of the General
Assembly Theo-Ben Gurirab will addressed the meeting, followed by
about sixty speakers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
