<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Budget Surplus Rises to 115 Billion Dollars in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27(Xinhua) -- The U.S. government Monday
estimated the budget surplus in fiscal 1999 should hit at least
115 billion dollars, the largest in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
The news was announced by President Clinton at the White House
early Monday. "It is a landmark achievement for our economy,"
President Clinton said before leaving on a trip to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
The larger-than-expected surplus likely will prompt new
Republican calls for major tax cuts for Americans. Clinton vetoed
a 792 billion dollars tax cut bill last week as "too big, too
bloated" and urged passage of a cut in the range of 250 billion to
300 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The president called anew on Republicans to work with his
administration on fixing Social Security, Medicare and other
problems.
</P>
<P>
"We can do all that and still have an affordable tax cut for
the middle class and pay down our debt so that by 2015 we are
debt-free for the first time since 1835, when Andrew Jackson was
president," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders are struggling to adjourn Congress by Oct.
29. They suggested Clinton's veto had killed chances for sweeping
tax reductions this year.
</P>
<P>
The higher surplus figure "is further proof that we're on the
right road to prosperity," Clinton said. "Our nation has come a
long way in a short time. In 1992, the budget deficit was 290
billion dollars, projected to rise above 400 billion dollars this
year," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the administration had estimated the surplus
for fiscal 1999 _ which ends Thursday _ at 99 billion dollars, but
the strong economy and larger than expected tax revenues pushed
the figure higher. The 115 billion dollars figure would break the
record 69 billion dollars surplus last year.
</P>
<P>
Even after adjusting for inflation, it is still the largest
surplus in U.S. history, Clinton administration said. The 1999
surplus would be about 1.3 percent of the gross domestic product,
the largest on this basis since 1951. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
