<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges International Community to Reaffirm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday urged the international Community to reaffirm
its commitment to the world's island developing nations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the special session of the United Nations General
Assembly on small islands, Annan said "By working with small
islands on their problems, we can find solutions for ours.
Brighter horizons for small islands can mean brighter horizons for
the world in general."
</P>
<P>
On the problems facing the small islands, Annan said there are
three:
</P>
<P>
-- The built-in constraints. Most small islands have not only
limited resources, whether land, human and financial. Many lie in
the path of hurricanes and cyclones.
</P>
<P>
-- The Environmental problems. The include climate changes,
freshwater shortages, inadequate waste management, over-fishing,
marine population and the threat of accidents involving transports
of hazardous wastes.
</P>
<P>
-- A set of challenges linked with globalization. Tourism is
both a blessing and a bane, bringing jobs but putting strains on
water supplies and ecosystems. Trade brings much-needed goods, but
liberalization and an end to special trade preferences will make
it harder for some of the products of small islands to compete.
</P>
<P>
Annan said small islands had done as much as they could to
manage their problems, and the international community, as fellow
inhabitants of the world island, should provide funding,
technology and other assistance in a spirit not only of solidarity
but of enlightened self-interest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
