<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDI Down 11 Percent in 1998 From 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The total volume of foreign
direct investment (FDI) in 1998 was 85 billion U.S. dollars, 11
percent down against the 1997 record, but the total in 1998 was
still the second highest ever and was about 3 billion dollars more
than that in 1996, according to a United Nations report published
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"In past years, the overall total was highly affected by FDI to
China which received FDI flows of about 45.5 billion in 1998,
exceeding the previous year's level by 1 billion dollars according
to revised estimates," said the United Nations Conference for
Trade and Development (UNCTAD) in its World Investment Report 1999:
Foreign Direct Investment and the Challenge of Development.
</P>
<P>
China not only accounted for well over half of total FDI flows
into the region, but was the third largest recipient in the world
behind only the United States and the United Kingdom, said the
UNCTAD.
</P>
<P>
Against the background of the Asian crisis, the UNCTAD said,
South Korea received its largest ever volume of FDI inflows at 5.1
billion dollars, a four-fold gain over its annual average in the
first half of the 1990s, and 2.3 billion above the 1997 volume,
making South Korea a net recipient after having been a net FDI
outflow country since the start of the decade.
</P>
<P>
As for South-East Asia, inflows to Malaysia and Singapore were
down 27 percent and 26 percent respectively. Hardest hit of all
was Indonesia, where FDI inflows turned negative with divestment
of 356 million dollars, compared to inflows of 4.7 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, rising levels of mergers and acquisitions pushed
inflows to Thailand to nearly 7 billion dollars, over 3 billion
more than those in 1997. The Philippines also enjoyed record
inflows.
</P>
<P>
In South Asia, Bangladesh experienced fast growth of FDI
inflows in 1998, particularly in energy. However, flows into India
fell by around 1 billion dollars to 2.3 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD said that low oil prices last year impacted FDI into
West Asia, with 1998 volume remaining almost the same as in 1997,
at 4.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the UN agency said, "Plans to expand oil and gas
production capacity in Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, United Arab Emirates
and Yemen, and the opening up of the petroleum sector to foreign
investors in Kuwait and the Islamic Republic of Iran should lead
to increase in FDI." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
