<HEADLINE> Mideast Airlines Favor Airbus Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Airlines of the Middle
East and North Africa will purchase 620 Airbus planes at a cost of
50 billion U.S. dollars between now and 2018, according to a
latest report prepared by the Airbus Industries.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 338 planes will be needed to meet expected
growth in passengers and 282 planes to replace old carriers,
predicted the report.
</P>
<P>
Airbus Industries Deputy Chairman for Strategic Planning
Affairs Adam Brown announced the details of the report in Dubai on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Brown said that the growth rate of passengers in the Middle
East and North Africa will be higher than that in North America.
</P>
<P>
The major airlines of the Middle East and North Africa have
opted for Airbus planes for their future travel industry, he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Airbus has also succeeded in selling its planes
to the Middle East airlines for the year 1999, without giving
detailed figures.
</P>
<P>
Airbus accounts for 59 percent of the world sales of
airplanes, he said. 
</P>
