<HEADLINE> Symposium on Development of Coastal Megalopolises Opens in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 experts and
government officials from a dozen countries today gathered in
Hangzhou, capital of east China's Zhejiang Province, to discuss
the development of super-large coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
The participants at the three-day International Symposium on
Coastal Super-Large Cities will discuss ways of maintaining
sustainable development of the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Chen Lianzeng, deputy director of the National Bureau of
Oceanography, said at the opening ceremony that the large coastal
cities are keen to solve such problems as fresh water supplies,
pollution, transportation, ground sinking, and natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that the participants will be able
to find ways to help solve these thorny problems.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that by the year 2015, there will be about 16
cities in the world with a population of more than 10 million.
</P>
<P>
China now has 500 million people living in its coastal areas,
accounting for 40 percent of its total population.  
</P>
