<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- A plan to cancel up to 27 billion dollars in debt owed by
the world's most desperately poor countries won key financial
backing from major industrial governments Sunday, clearing the way
for funds that now flow to foreign creditors to stay home instead
to pay for schools and clinics.
</P>
<P>
-- Congressional Republicans are pressing a new round of
confrontation with the White House over environmental protections,
adding one more large complication to the already difficult task
of finishing work on the annual spending bills.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The head of the Bank of Japan strongly hinted that he was
prepared to reverse course and act to halt a three-month rise in
the value of the yen, before it chokes off Japan's fragile
economic recovery and sets off further clashes with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State K. Albright met in New York with the
man expected to lead an independent East Timor and warned
Indonesia that it risks losing American aid and investment unless
it protects refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Chechnya's capital was attacked by Russian warplanes for the
fourth day as Yeltsin's defense minister refused to rule out an
invasion of the breakaway republic that humiliated Moscow in the
1994-96 separatist war. An estimated 13,000 Russian troops are now
on the border.
</P>
<P>
-- Colombia will let the peso float against the dollar,
abandoning the central bank's efforts to maintain trading bands
amid heavy selling pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
