<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Calls for Reform of EU Agriculture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, Britain, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The British
Government on Monday reiterated its call for the reform of the
European Union's common agricultural program (CAP).
</P>
<P>
British Secretary for Agriculture Nick Brown, addressing the
Labor Party's annual conference here, urged reducing production
subsidies for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"I believe we should have a common approach to agriculture
throughout the European Single Market, but I want to transform the
CAP so that there is less emphasis on production subsidies that
force prices up," he said.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he said there should be more emphasis on rural
development measures which recognize the role played by
agriculture in rural life, in rural economies, in protecting the
environment and in shaping the landscape, he said.
</P>
<P>
Europeans cannot go on producing food surplus in heavily
subsidized regimes, "food which is either dumped on world markets,
with damaging effects on producers outside Europe or put into
store, building stockpiles of food that will never be eaten," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Also, he stated the "major priorities" facing the Labor
Government at the moment as "making further progress with
agricultural reform during the next WTO round, making maximum
possible use of new opportunities to pursue Labor's countryside
policies through the Rural Development Regulation and helping
British farming through the present deep and enduring fall in farm
incomes." 
</P>
</TEXT>
