<HEADLINE> Share Prices Closes Lower in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed lower in
Tokyo Monday, hit by erratic movements in the foreign exchange
market despite monetary officials from the Group of Seven (G-7)
nations expressing concern about the yen's recent rise against the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped 50.67 points, or 0.30
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 16,821.06.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, edged down 1.04 points or 0.07 percent to 1,
429.38.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index topped 17,000 in early trading in line with
the dollar's rebound against the yen, following the G-7 meeting
held in Washington Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index, however, lost ground after the dollar dropped
again in the afternoon, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 346.72 million
shares from 640.36 million shares last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 665 to 525, with 141 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar jumped to the
106 yen level in early trading but later fell to the 103 yen level,
with the Group of Seven (G-7) statement of concern about the yen's
rise having only short-lived effect.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was quoted at 104.12-15 yen, down from
105.57-62 yen at 9 a.m., and 103.90-104.00 yen late last Friday in
New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
