<HEADLINE> Members of SEHK, HKFE Approve Merger Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Stock
Exchange of Hong Kong and Hong Kong Futures Exchange have approved
the proposed demutualization and merger of the two exchanges and
associated clearing houses.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (
SAR) and the Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing Limited (HKEC), the
holding company set up on July 8 to pave the way for the merger,
expressed their welcome to the approval today.
</P>
<P>
The approval is a major step towards the strategic market
structure reform, initiated by Financial Secretary Donald Tsang in
his budget report in March this year, said Rafael Hui, acting
financial secretary of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
This reform is essential for Hong Kong to enhance its
competitiveness and reinforce its position as international
financial center, Hui said.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to the sanction by the court of the merger on
October 11. Meanwhile, we are drafting the enabling legislation
for the merger, with the target of introducing the bill to the
Legislative Council in November," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the approval, HKEC Chairman Charles Lee said that
HKEC will actively proceed with all necessary preparatory work for
the implementation of the merger.
</P>
<P>
According to the current timetable, and subject to the court
sanction of the merger and the passage of the enabling legislation
by the Legislative Council, the merger is expected to take effect
in late January or early February 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
