<HEADLINE> Entertainment Giants Eye China Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Sumner Redstone, chairman
and chief executive officer of the U.S. entertainment company
Viacom, said here today that Asia, particularly China, has become
the area that multinational mass communications companies are
highly focused on.
</P>
<P>
He is here to attend the '99 Fortune Global Forum that the Time-
Warner Group's Fortune magazine sponsored.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here this afternoon that over the
next decade, the number of households receive multichannel
programs will boom and triple the advertisement sales of TV
stations in the area. He said that since Asia has two billion
people under the age of 35, the area will yield fantastic payoff
for international entertainment companies entering the market.
</P>
<P>
Viacom's MTV channel has already reached 40 million households
in China. Redstone said that the company will launch a music
website dedicated exclusively to Chinese speaking music fans.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the world's major mass communications company
News Corporation set up its first resident representative office
in China. It has set up a website jointly with one of China's
largest national newspaper People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
Laurie Smith, chief representative of the News Corporation
resident in China, said that all major international mass
communications companies are actively looking for opportunities to
set up partnership with Chinese media and entertainment business
through various means.
</P>
<P>
Walter Disney, 20th Century Fox under the News Corporation and
Paramount under Viacom sold ten hit motion pictures to China every
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
