<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Trying to Improve Reproductive Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has been enhancing
protection of reproductive health rights through supportive
policies over the past few years, a report released Monday here by
a regional workshop shows.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, the country has adopted the national
population policy whose overall goal is to improve the quality of
life and standard of living.
</P>
<P>
The country's constitution, enacted in 1995, states that laws,
cultures, customs or traditions which are against the dignity,
welfare or interest of women or which undermine their status, are
prohibited by the constitution. These include harmful practices
like early marriages that have negative health related effects.
</P>
<P>
The government adopted a national gender policy in 1997 whose
key aspects are to integrate gender into development efforts at
all levels for planning, resource allocation, and implementation
of development programs.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the government is now in the process of
developing a reproductive health policy which will focus on safe
motherhood, family planning, HIV/AIDS prevention, adolescent
health and genital tract cancer.
</P>
<P>
Although Uganda still has one of the highest adolescent
pregnancy in Sub-Sahara Africa, the government is confident that
more and better legislative work would be done to improve
reproductive health of the public in general and women in
particular, the report noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
