<HEADLINE> Oil Price Increase Set to Take Effect in Philippines This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Another round of oil price
increase is set to take effect in the Philippines this week due to
the rise of crude oil cost in the world market, officials of
Pilipinas Shell and Petron Corporation said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with reporters, Shell Vice President for
Corporate Affairs Rey Gamboa said the increase will take effect
before September 30. He assured it will not go beyond one peso but
not lower than 58 centavos per liter.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that prices of diesel oil and liquefied
petroleum gas will remain the same.
</P>
<P>
Gamboa said the increase is based on the current cost of crude
oil in the world market pegged at 17 U.S. dollars to 21 dollars
per barrel.
</P>
<P>
A new round of oil hikes will also take effect next month
which, Gamboa explained, would be due to an increase in the price
of crude oil in the international market.
</P>
<P>
International oil suppliers have sent out advisories to the
local oil firms that there would be a four-dollar increase in the
price of crude oil next month. The purchasing cost of the product
will rise to 25 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Gamboa said oil companies may be forced to hold back any price
adjustments for oil and other petroleum products if the government
agrees to reduce specific taxes and duties imposed on them.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Petron Corp. and Pilipinas Shell raised the prices
of their oil products by an average of 35 centavos a liter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
