<HEADLINE> Korean Athletes Swing High at China's National Minorities Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- With the flower-decorated
ropes waggling, golden bells jingling and their colorful skirts
floating in the wind, two Korean girls swinging in the air seemed
like fairies out of the clouds.
</P>
<P>
Kim Chunhua, a 18-year-old middle school student and her
partner from the Korean minority nationality won the pairs
swinging event by touching the bells 85 times within the
stipulated time of 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
A pair of competitors from Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region,
who are twin sisters, took the silvers with one less touch in the
regular time.
</P>
<P>
Swinging competition was one of the hottest sports at the
current Chinese National Games for Traditional Sports of Minority
Nationalities, which opened here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The big crowd here is really unexpected," Kim said. "I'm
very happy. The hard training has finally paid off," she said.
</P>
<P>
With the game of swinging more and more prevailing, some people
are considering to promote it, as an international sport, to other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure we would win if there are world championships for the
sport," said Li Xuexiu, leader of the Jilin Provincial swinging
team and a four-time participant of the National Minorities Games.
</P>
<P>
Mainly a traditional folk game, swinging has enjoyed a great
popularity among residents of South Korea and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Many experts in China have made great efforts and finally
succeeded in transforming it into an organized sport, with
generations of talented players emerging in recent years, he added.
</P>
<P>
Research has been commenced in some sports middle schools in
Jilin, a northeastern Chinese province with the largest Korean
minority nationality community, to make the game safer and more
attractive to TV audiences.
</P>
<P>
Besides individual and pairs contest for bell-touching event,
there are also height competitions for both individuals and pairs,
at the Games here. The player who swings the highest is declared
the winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
