<HEADLINE> Opinion Polls Add Confusion Over Indian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- No clear picture has
emerged from the four phases of the ongoing Marathon election
battles in India, which have been carried on mainly between the
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) and its rival, the Congress, ever
since last August.
</P>
<P>
Opinion or exit polls by several agencies of the country seemed
to have added more confusion over the possible winner of the
pollings to the lower house of parliament, which began early this
month.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, an exit poll by the official Doordarshan two
hours after the end of the fourth phase of polling concluded that
the BJP-led National Democratic Alliance (NDA) was heading for a
simple majority.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, three more agencies put out results of their polls
and each of them had reached a set of confusion that did not tally
with the other.
</P>
<P>
An interesting feature of the results announced separately by
the three agencies was that two of them said the Congress might
cross the 200-seat mark and emerge as the single largest party
while the third said categorically that NDA would get an absolute
majority despite "some minor losses" in the third and fourth
phases of polling.
</P>
<P>
The agencies which predicted a comfortable and absolute
majority for the NDA are normally commissioned by those who have
close relations with the BJP, or even BJP's members of parliament
(MP).
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, most of those which predicted results just the
opposite are pro-Congress agencies such as Lokmat poll which was
carried out by a newspaper owned by a Congress MP.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account all the four exit polls, Jain Television,
owned by a former BJP MP, said NDA was likely to get 236 out of a
total of 543 seats in Lok Sabha while the Congress was set to win
only 127 seats, giving a clear advantage of 109 seats over the
Congress-led alliance.
</P>
<P>
In a complete contrast, the Lokmat exit poll predicted that the
Congress and its allies would emerge as the single largest group
while the NDA would be in the second position with only 200 seats.
</P>
<P>
However, well-informed independent sources here said the
BJP-led coalition would have comfortable win and secure over 300
seats in the elections, the third in four years in the South Asian
country.
</P>
<P>
If the projections turn out right, the BJP could overtake the
Congress as the single largest party after the third of October
when the last phase of the polling is to be launched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
