<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers in Eastern China Create Environmental Miracle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Some foreign scholars have been
amazed at the success in Anhui Province's Yinshang County, which
has two villages listed among the world's 500 top successful
environmental protection units.
</P>
<P>
This miracle of transformation began with two brothers, Zhang
Jiashun and Zhang Jiawang, the heads of the villages of Xiaozhang
and Balihe, respectively, who are known here as the "ecology
brothers".
</P>
<P>
Before the mid-1970s, the average annual income of Xiaozhang's
farmers was 45 yuan (5.4 U.S. dollars) and per hectare grain
output was 825 kilograms. But by the mid-1970s, Zhang Jiashun led
the villagers in planting trees, developing water conservation
projects, building hydro-electric power stations, transforming
farmland, and digging wells. Energy-saving stoves were introduced
to reduce the use of firewood and methane-generating pits were dug
to provide clean energy. The mud from the fish ponds was used as
manure on fields.
</P>
<P>
The village has built 45 forest shelter belts 50 km long in all.
The improved environment has helped increase agricultural output.
Grain output has climbed to 16,500 kilograms per hectare and the
farmer's annual income has increased to 2,800 yuan per capita.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, the village was recognized for its environmental
protection by the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP), and
Zhang Jiashun was given a UNEP award in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Balihe Village is 30 km away. There, Zhang Jiawang led farmers
in providing irrigation and drainage systems for 2,500 hectares of
land. They also developed 370 hectares of lotus ponds, 600
hectares of paddies, and 187 hectares of ponds for special types
of fish and aquatic vegetables.
</P>
<P>
With the improvements in the local ecological environment,
every family in the village has its own fish pond and farmers'
average annual income has increased to 3,200 yuan, from less than
200 yuan before the 1980s. And Zhang Jiawang was listed among the
world's top 500 individuals for their outstanding work in
environmental protection in 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
