<HEADLINE> Philippine Congress Urged to Amend Anti-Rape Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine woman Senator Loren
Legarda has urged Congress to consider amending the Rape Victim
Assistance and Protection Act, so that only female physicians may
conduct examination on female rape victims, Philippine News Agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It is degrading for female victims of rape, particularly
minors, to be examined by a male doctor. Some people even say it
is just like the victim is being raped twice," Legarda said.
</P>
<P>
The traumatized victim adamantly refused to be examined by a
male medico-legal officer, she added.
</P>
<P>
Legarda, meanwhile, appealed to her colleagues for support on
ensuring that the Rape Victim Assistance and Protection Act is
adequately funded in the proposed 2000 national budget.
</P>
<P>
Passed in February 1998, Legarda lamented that up to now, the
law has remained unfunded to the tune of 120 million pesos (3
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The law seeks to establish at least one rape crisis center in
every province and city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
