<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Oil firms Get Ultimatum on Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Major oil and gas companies
operating in Nigeria's Niger River Delta have been given six weeks
to submit proposals on remedial measures over environmental
pollution to the Ministry of Environment.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper Monday quoted Nigerian Environment
Minister of State, Imeh Okopido, as saying: "it was disheartening
to note that in several of the industrial establishments, waste
treatment procedures were not followed through, exposing the
environment, including humans, to unimaginable hazards and
nuisance from these wastes."
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the end of a visit to the country's
southeast oil yielding states.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government was anxious to see improvement in
waste management practices in the oil and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
"It is not just lead. The benzene is our greatest concern.
Benzene is the one that destroys the genes of humans and that is
part of the petroleum products that are emptied into our rivers
affecting our children and even adults," Okopido emphasized.
</P>
