<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FOREX Market to Be Liberalized in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's foreign exchange
market will be liberalized by the end of October with the daily
Inter-bank Foreign Exchange Market (IFEM) reintroduced, Nigeria's
Central Bank Governor Joseph Sanusi has said.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of IFEM will bring to an end the Autonomous
Foreign Exchange Market (AFEM) through which the Central Bank of
Nigeria has intervened weekly for the past 13 years in sales of
foreign exchange to banks, local newspaper This Day Monday quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor made the remarks in Washington during
the on- going annual meeting of the World Bank Group and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
According to him, "AFEM will run parallel to IFEM for one or
two weeks, after which it shall be scrapped for a liberalized
environment."
</P>
<P>
Sanusi admitted that the central bank made an attempt to
liberalize the foreign exchange market in March this year with
the introduction of IFEM, but it failed to take off because
certain things were not properly done.
</P>
<P>
He noted that with the introduction of IFEM, the oil companies
would have the right to sell their forex directly to the market,
thereby allowing banks to buy as much forex as they require.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign exchange market will now become fluid and that the
central bank will cease to intervene on a weekly basis, except it
becomes necessary to do so," he added.
</P>
<P>
In the past, oil companies are required to sell their forex
proceeds to the central bank, which will subsequently be sold to
the banks through AFEM.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the decision to liberalize the forex market,
bank executives who spoke to This Day all lauded the decision,
saying "it had been long over due."
</P>
<P>
Jim Ovia, managing director of Zenith International Bank, was
quoted as saying that with the liberalization of the market, the
local currency naira would be allowed to float and find its
actual value against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization of the forex market in Nigeria is one of the
monetary reform measures the IMF has been pushing for under a
medium term economic program.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has held the view that the central bank should stop its
weekly intervention in AFEM and artificially peg the value of the
naira against the dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
