<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Spend $200 Million on Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 27 (Xinhua ) -- Nigerian government, together
with international agencies, will pool some 200 million U.S.
dollars for the advancement of science, engineering and technology
in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
The program is to be anchored by the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) and
strongly committed by Nigerian government, according to the
Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo has launched a Special
Framework Plan of Action to ensure the scheme's success, said the
paper.
</P>
<P>
The special plan, according to Fola Osotimehin, a UNESCO
science policy adviser in Paris, France, is intended to reinforce
international co- operation with Nigeria in the efforts at
national reconstruction and development and strengthening of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
Besides, science and technology, education, culture,
communication, informatics and information are other sectors that
would benefit from the plan.
</P>
<P>
Osotimehin, who coordinated a Consultative Forum on Budgeting
for Scientific, Engineering and Technological Activities in Abuja
last week, said that Nigeria had invested in the establishment of
a fairly adequate Science and Technology (S&AMP;T) infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that the infrastructure needed to be
reinforced and modernized.
</P>
<P>
"A major urgent requirement is the reform of the national
science and technology system and this is the main goal of the
science component of the Special Nigeria-UNESCO Plan of Action,"
Osotimehin said.
</P>
<P>
The reform being pursued is aimed at increasing the
effectiveness of the national science and technology system,
particularly by ensuring that S&AMP;T outputs are used in attaining
important macro-economic objectives for the benefit of the
masses. Such benefits include job creation, diversification of
the economy, promotion of exports and protection of the
environment.
</P>
<P>
The reform, which will involve the evaluation of S&AMP;T policies,
programs and institutions, is expected to be undertaken during the
next rolling plan.
</P>
<P>
Osotimehin said the preparation of next year's budget is an
opportunity to launch the reform process. He added that there is
a need for science and technology to address the economic needs
of the country rather than scientists being concerned about their
professional competence. "That is important, but we should not
downplay the economic outcome of science and technology," he
said.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO Representative to Nigeria and ECOWAS, Emmanuel Apea,
reiterated at the close of the four-day forum, which began last
Monday, that science and technology should play proper role in
the national efforts for economic growth and national
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Jiang Zemin Addresses Fortune Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here this evening that China's future development will
affect both the country and the world and called on foreign
business leaders to participate in China's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Jiang was speaking at a banquet marking the opening of the '99
Fortune Global Forum in the Shanghai International Convention
Center in Shanghai's flourishing Pudong New Area. The theme of the
three-day forum is "China: the Next 50 Years."
</P>
<P>
Extending warm welcome on behalf the Chinese government and
people to "the friends who come to forum", Jiang said that China
is a large developing socialist country and its future development
will not only directly affect the future of the Chinese people,
but will also have a major impact on the development and progress
of Asia and the world.
</P>
<P>
"All you business leaders present tonight are outstanding
achievers in your respective fields. You have a wealth of
successful experiences and strategic vision," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"Since you've set your eyes on China, China welcomes you. China
's modernization drive needs your participation, and China's
economic development will also offer you tremendous opportunities,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 chairmen, presidents and chief executive officers of
multinational companies including General Motors, Ford, Mitsui,
Royal Dutch/Shell Group, are present at the forum, the largest
ever sponsored by the Time-Warner Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also expressed his hope that Chinese enterprises will
learn from the advanced experiences of foreign enterprises. "They
must go out and temper themselves in the winds and storms of
economic globalization, and build up their own competitiveness."
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government will offer good terms to and create a
better environment for foreign enterprises investing in China," he
promised.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that over the past more than hundred
years, the Chinese people have experienced various vicissitudes of
life. In the course of vigorous struggle they have accomplished a
great historic transformation. Over the past 50 years, New China
has made tremendous development achievements that have drawn
worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
"More than 50 years ago, I was attending university in Shanghai,
and was well aware of the poverty, backwardness and weakness of
Old China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It was at that time that I decided to devote myself to the
noble cause of building an independent, free, democratic, united,
prosperous and powerful New China. And I have been struggling for
that to this very day."
</P>
<P>
Jiang became mayor of Shanghai 14 years ago, and has
experienced the process of reform, opening-up and modernization in
this China's biggest city.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure that all of you have seen with your own eyes the
changes that have been taking place day by day in Shanghai. The
growth of Shanghai presents one aspect of the tremendous changes
taking place throughout China," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the Chinese people are fully confident
of the country's prospects in the next 50 years at a time when
mankind is about to step into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese people will continue to follow firmly and
unswervingly the path of reform and opening-up," Jiang said. "Our
goal is to basically realize modernization by the middle of the
next century, to make China a powerful, democratic and civilized
modern socialist country, and to achieve the great rejuvenation of
the Chinese nation."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Chinese people have always respected
the dignity and value of human beings, insisted on independence,
loved freedom and peace, and treasured national unity.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that the world is a colorful one where the people
of all countries follow the path of development they have chosen
and pursue their own ideals. This is an inevitable demand for and
fundamental sign of the progress of human civilization and world
democracy. It is therefore an irresistible historical trend.
</P>
<P>
He said that China believes that the different social systems
and different political beliefs that exist in the world at present
should not be used as obstacles against normal economic and
technological cooperation and exchanges of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
At the turn of the century and millennium, the initiative for
development lies in the hands of the people of all countries,
Jiang said, and called for the people of all countries to make
joint efforts for the noble cause of promoting peace and
development of mankind.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that China will have an even brighter future
as will the future of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also took the opportunity to express once again
condolences to Taiwan compatriots who have suffered from a series
of severe earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
Among those attending the banquet are Chinese Vice-Premier Qian
Qichen, Secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) Huang Ju and Secretary of the
Secretariat of the CPC Central Committee Zeng Qinghong.
</P>
<P>
This year's forum is the largest in the history of the Fortune
Global Forum. More than 800 delegates from both China and abroad
will attend the meeting. Among the attendants are 300 chairmen,
presidents and chief executive officers of multinational companies
and heads of 200 large Chinese companies, as well as celebrities
from the political and economic circles.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 of the world's top 500 enterprises are presented at
the meeting, far exceeding the number in the previous two meetings.
</P>
<P>
The attendants also include more than 40 high-ranking officials
from China's central and local governments.
</P>
<P>
The forum has also attracted nearly 600 journalists from
Chinese and international media.  
</P>
</TEXT>
