<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Information Technology Boosts China's Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The fast-growing information
technology has dramatically pushed China's education development
forward, which brought about profound transformation in the
country's education cause, said Chen Zhili, China's minister of
education at the '99 Fortune Global Forum here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Fortune Information Technology Roundtable, Chen
said that with popularization of information technology, China has
established a large group of radio and TV universities, education
TV stations and centers, and established three satellite
educational channels as well as more than 16,000 ground receivers.
</P>
<P>
Educational and multimedia software are widely used in teaching
as well, said the minister, adding that the Chinese education and
research network (CERNET) has so far connected with over 400
universities, and more than 300,000 network users are on line each
day.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that information technology has provided technical
support for the country's distance-learning program. Through radio,
satellite TV and the Internet, China has trained an army of
teachers, and effectively transmitted education courses to islands
and plateaux as well as mountainous regions at lower costs.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, multimedia and network technology has already caused
major changes in the thinking, philosophy, model, methods and
strategies in the country's education development, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Edward S. Tian, president and chief executive officer of the
China NetCom Corporation, also expressed his views at today's
Fortune Information Technology Roundtable, saying that China will
become a wired country and an on-line nation by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
He noted that by 2003, there will have had 80 to 100 million
people using computerized information terminals or appliances in
China. Among them there will be 20 million mobile internet
subscribers, 10 million broadband interactive users. China will by
that time have at least five to eight nationwide high speed IP/WDM
backbones in place, and on-line education will become one of the
basic applications, Tian added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
