<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Indonesian Ministers to Hold 2 Posts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Some Indonesian ministers
will hold two posts concurrently after their colleagues resigned
from their positions, State Secretary Muladi told reporters here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Development Supervision/State
Administrative Reform Hartarto will serve concurrently as
coordinating minister for economy and industry, replacing
Ginandjar Kartasasmita who resigned following his appointment as a
member of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR)'s regional
faction from West Java province.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Transmigration Hendro Priyono has been assigned by
President B.J. Habibie to also hold the position of the manpower
minister, replacing Fahmi Idris, who has also resigned following
his appointment as an MPR member.
</P>
<P>
The post of minister of housing and resettlement, which was
previously occupied by Theo L. Sambuaga, will be served by
Minister for Public Works Rahmadi B.S.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki Usman, who holds the two ministerial posts of tourism
and investment, would be replaced by Minister for Transportation
Giri Suseno and Minister for Research and Technology Zuhal for the
respective portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki has been appointed as a member in the MPR of the
faction from the Indonesian Economist Association.
</P>
<P>
Muladi added the post of State Minister for Food A.M. Saefuddin
will be served concurrently by Minister for Agriculture Soleh
Solahudin while the post of state minister for youth and sports
will be held also by Minister for Education and Culture Juwono
Sudarsono.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Political Affairs Feisal Tanjung will
also hold the position of Home Affairs Minister Syarwan Hamid, who
will be appointed as a member of the MPR.
</P>
<P>
The new MPR consists of 500 members of the House of
Representatives (DPR), 135 delegates from regions and 65 delegates
from various groups.
</P>
<P>
The two-stage general session of the MPR is to begin on October
1, when 700 new DPR and MPR members will be sworn in to choose the
new leaders of the two bodies. the final part of the session, the
presidential election, is scheduled for November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
