<HEADLINE> Gold Rush Drives Australian Stocks Higher at Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A gold rush supported the
Australian sharemarket Monday, allowing it to buck offshore trends
and finish firmly in positive territory.
</P>
<P>
Strength in the banking sector also helped the local market
trade higher on the day.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index added 17.7 points to close
at 2,911.1 after dipping to a low of 2,889.4 earlier in the
session.
</P>
<P>
Losses on Wall Street on Friday night and on the majority of
world markets failed to undermine the local bourse with the All
Industrials Index gaining 25.4 points to 4,994.5 and the All
Resources Index putting on 13.7 points to 1,297.8.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector went up 81.6 points to 6,190 with sector
heavyweight National Australia Bank putting on 30 cents to 23
Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank rallied 60.8 cents to 23.71
Australian dollars, ANZ inched up 6 cents to 10.24 Australian
dollars and Westpac firmed 8.8 cents to 9.65 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary national turnover was 458.11 million stocks traded
for 1.01 billion Australian dollars (666.6 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Falling stocks outpaced rising ones by 647 to 574 and 415
others remained steady. 
</P>
