<HEADLINE> Singapore Shares Fall Through 2,000-Point Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Share prices fell sharply
breaking through the sensitive 2,000-point mark Monday as the
market shrugged off the weekend announcement of a strong hike in
Singapore's August manufacturing output and focused on regional
bourses.
</P>
<P>
Worries over the situation in Indonesia and a possible hike of
U.S. interest rates pushed the benchmark Straits Times Index (STI)
below the 2,000-point level to close at 1,990.38 points with a
loss of 28.63 points.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover contracted to 186.21 million units valued at
349.25 million Singapore dollars (205.15 million U.S. dollars).
Losers outstripped gainers by 316 to 16, nearly 20 times, with 119
counters remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was a 17.84 million parcel by TMC which was
transacted at 0.46 Singapore dollars per share. The second mostly
heavily traded stock was Gen Int which had 15.77 million units
done. AFP was next with 12.49 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS topped the actives list of the day running up 50 cents to
close at 18.7 Singapore dollars. KhongGuan went up 20 cents to
finish at 2.6 Singapore dollars. SIA and SIA 200 inched up 10
cents to end at 16.9 and 16.8 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH was the biggest loser of the day, sliding
80 cents to close at 26.7 Singapore dollars. Pac Cent shed 50
cents to finish at 9.95 Singapore dollars while CityDev sank 35
cents to end at 8.25 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that the market was under pressure from the start
but fell sharply as the index broke through 2,000 points a little
after the midday break.
</P>
<P>
They said investors were reluctant to initiate fresh moves due
to political uncertainty in Indonesia, the volatile yen and ahead
of a decision on U.S. interest rates by the Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
A technical analyst was quoted as saying, "It is going to be
like this for a while." 
</P>
</TEXT>
