<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Re-elected with Over 90 Percent "Yes" Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak has been re-elected with 93.79 percent "Yes" votes in a
referendum on his presidency, the interior minister announced on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Habib el-Adli said on national television that the "Yes" vote
stood at 17,554,856, or 93.79 of the valid votes in the referendum
on Sunday. The "No" vote was 1,162,525, or 6.21 percent, el-Adli
said.
</P>
<P>
The 71-year-old sitting president was the only candidate in the
yes-or-no referendum.
</P>
<P>
The turnout was 79.2 percent, or 18.957,893 of the nearly 24
million eligible voters, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time the "Yes" vote was less than 95 percent
in a presidential referendum in Egypt. In the past three
referendums, Mubarak got more than 95 percent "Yes" votes.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak became president in 1981 after the former president,
Anwar Sadat, was assassinated by Islamic radicals. He was
re-elected in 1987 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
Under Egypt's constitution, the country does not hold direct,
multi-candidate presidential elections. Instead, the parliament,
People's Assembly, nominates one candidate, and a referendum must
be held to approve the nomination. The parliament dominated by
Mubarak's National Democratic Party nominated him in July.
</P>
<P>
During the past 18 years, Mubarak has pushed forward the peace
process with Israel and carried out a privatization program which
has helped Egypt maintain a more diverse and open economy in the
Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
