<HEADLINE> Malaysian Navy Gets Two Corvettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Malaysian Navy
(RMN) Monday took delivery of two Italian-built corvettes.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held at the RMN base in Lumut, some 290
kilometers northwest of here, Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the ships, RMN Deputy Chief Rear Admiral Mohamed
Hussin Tamby said Malaysia had acquired them with a view to
contributing toward the peace and stability of the Southeast Asian
region.
</P>
<P>
"The purchase should not be construed as part of an arms race
in this region," Bernama quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a maritime nation, Malaysia needed a
well-equipped navy able to discharge its big responsibility of
safeguarding the country's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
These are the last two of four corvettes ordered by Malaysia
from the Fincantierri-Cantieri Norali Italiana company at a total
cost of 260 million U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Both ships are equipped with sophisticated weapons including
surface to surface missiles, super rapid fire guns as well as
compact naval guns, according to Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The ships measuring 62.3 meters in length and weighing 705 tons
were commissioned by Defense Minister Abang Abu Bakar Mustapha at
the La Spezia Shipyard in Italy on July 31 and will join the
navy's 24th Corvette Squadron. 
</P>
