<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Raids to Continue on Chechnya, Says Russian Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Strikes will be made until the last gangster is destroyed,"
the minister said after a meeting with Prime Minister Vladimir
Putin, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The conference was also attended by First Deputy Prime Minister
Nikolai Aksyonenko, Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov, Interior
Minister Vladimir Rushailo and Federal Security Service Director
Nikolai Patrushev.
</P>
<P>
The officials discussed the mounting flow of refugees from
Chechnya since federal airplanes started bombing raids four days
ago, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Russian media reported that thousands of refugees have fled to
the neighboring republics of Daghestan and Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
Rebel bases, arms depots, oil refineries, mobile communications
and television transmission facilities were among the targets of
the air raids. The radar at the Grozny airport and an AN-2
airplane, the only one functioning in Chechnya, were destroyed in
the first day of bombing.
</P>
<P>
In a newspaper interview published Monday, Prime Minister Putin
said Russian authorities are prepared to hold talks with Chechen
President Aslan Maskhadov, who is the legitimate leader of
Chechnya, provided that he denounces international terrorism and
sends his condolences in connection with those civilian deaths
which occurred in several Russian cities due to terrorist
explosions.
</P>
<P>
Putin was referring to several apartment building blasts in
Moscow and two other Russian cities that killed more than 300
people. Chechnya-based Islamic militants, with support from abroad,
are believed to be behind the explosions.
</P>
<P>
He said fighting terrorism is Russia's overriding goal. "Before
we deal with this, we cannot succeed in anything in the economy or
politics." 
</P>
</TEXT>
