<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Receives over 90 Percent "Yes" Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian sitting President
Hosni Mubarak received more than 90 percent "yes" votes in the
Sunday's referendum on his re-election, the interior minister said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Habib el-Adli visited Mubarak early in the day and briefed him
on the outcome of the referendum on the parliament nomination of
Mubarak for a new six-year term, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
El-Adli told the president that he got 93.79 percent "yes"
votes, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after the meeting that he will announce the
details of the referendum later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The poll started at 8:00 local time (0500 GMT) Sunday and ended
at 17:00 (14:00 GMT). Egypt set up 40,907 polling stations in 26
governorates nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In the past referendums, Mubarak received more than 95 percent
"yes" votes.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's constitution does not allow for a direct presidential
election. Instead, the parliament, the People's Assembly,
nominates one candidate for the presidency. A referendum must then
be held to endorse the nomination.
</P>
<P>
The parliament, which is dominated by Mubarak's National
Democratic Party, chose him for a fourth six-year term in
July. The voters are asked to say "yes" or "no" to the nominee.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was first elected president in 1981 after former
President Anwar Sadat was assassinated. He was re-elected in 1987
and 1993.
</P>
<P>
During the past 18 years, he has pushed forward the Arab-Israel
peace process and carried out an economic reform program which has
helped Egypt maintain one of the best economic performances in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 24 million people in the country of a population of 64
million are eligible voters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
