<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> - Mayon Evacuees Wary of Going Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The erratic character of Mt.
Mayon in the central Philippines scares many residents near and
around it, but evacuees are thinking of going back home,
Philippine News Agency(PNA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
At least 3,000 people fled their homes last week after the
volcano exploded for the second time in three months, the PNA
said.
</P>
<P>
Local government was quoted as saying its emergency funds will
not last for weeks feeding the evacuees but its officials could
not send them back home because of the risks.
</P>
<P>
"Nor could we turn down those who wanted to stay in evacuation
centers," said Governor Al Bichara of Albay province, where the
Mt. Mayon lies.
</P>
<P>
The risk is doubled specially during the rainy season since
disaster experts fear heavy rains might trigger an avalanche of
volcanic debris deposited up the Mayon's slopes.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology
(Phivolcs) has maintained a level Alert 2 Status on the Mayon.
</P>
<P>
Phivolcs expert Ed Laguerta said the volcano might just be
cleaning up debris of its past eruptions for a stronger blast.
</P>
<P>
The Mayon's first eruption this year was June 22, followed by
another one on September 22.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Philippine Vice President Gloria Arroyo visited
three evacuation centers in the province and released some 1 mill
ion pesos (25,000 U.S. dollars) for the continued construction of
the Mayon Rehabilitation Center.
</P>
<P>
Arroyo, concurrent secretary of social services and
development, said her department is ready should the Mayon assume
a violent character. 
</P>
</TEXT>
