<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Releases White Paper on Minorities Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 20,000-Chinese-word paper, entitled "National Minorities
Policy and its Practice in China", was released by the Information
Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
It is made up of five parts, with the following headings: a
united multi-ethnic country, adherence to equality and unity among
ethnic groups, regional autonomy for ethnic minorities, promoting
the common development of all ethnic groups, and preservation and
development of the cultures of ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
The paper goes over the history and progress of the country's
55 minorities groups, which account for 8.98 percent of the 1.2
billion population, and reviews the central government's policies
in handling issues concerning ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
"China has blazed a correct way for handling ethnic problems
and realizing the common prosperity of the various ethnic groups
in conformity with China's reality," the paper says.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper adds, due to the restrictions and influences
of historical and geographical factors, central and western China,
where most ethnic minority people live, lags far behind the
eastern coastal areas in development.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government attaches great importance to these
problems, and is taking measures to solve them."
</P>
<P>
The paper believes that as the country's reform and opening-up
drive develops, various ethnic groups of China will develop in a
still more rapid and healthy way, and relations between ethnic
groups marked by equality, unity and mutual help are certain to be
further consolidated and promoted in the coming 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The white paper is published in Chinese, English, French and
other languages. The English version runs into 43 pages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Web Addresses to Top 50,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The number of New Zealand
Web
addresses is expected to top 50,000 within half a year after a 34-
percent leap in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
Domain names registered in the ".nz" space leapt 81 percent to
reach 28,904 by the end of March. That number has since grown to
38,800 with no signs of the momentum slipping, New Zealand
InfoTech
Weekly reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Domainz, the organization which has managed the ".nz" domain
name
space since 1996, reaped its first net profit of more than 451,000
NZ
dollars (235,000 U.S. dollars) in the year to March 1999 thanks to

buoyant demand for ".nz" addresses.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Domainz will plow its profit back into
Internet development. It expects annual growth in the number of
registrations to remain at around 80 percent in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand with a population of about 3.8 million has the
third
highest number of country code domains per capita, just behind
Denmark and Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
