<HEADLINE> AIDS to Reduce Kenyan Life Expectancy to 42 years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Average life expectancy in
Kenya is to drop to 42 years from the present 50 by the year 2010
because of the killer AIDS disease.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Health Ministry warned that the AIDS death
will reach the 2.7 million mark while AIDS orphans will rise to
1.5 million by 2005, the East African Standard newspaper said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report released by the National AIDS/STD Control Program
said that 15 years of life expectancy have been lost due to the
pandemic. It projected that life expectancy, which had dropped
from 65 to 50, will fall to 42 year in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
It noted that cumulative AIDS deaths will hit the 2.7 million
mark by 2005 and the number of new cases recorded every year is to
top 240,000 by 2000, saying HIV prevalence is to increase from 14
percent of adult population in 1998 to 15 percent by 2005 and then
stabilize.
</P>
<P>
The number of AIDS orphans will rise from 860,000 at the turn
of the century to 1.5 million by 2005, the reported added.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that at present more than two million Kenyan
including 100, 000 children under five have been infected with HIV
and over 700,000 people have already died from AIDS since the
first AIDS case found in the country in 1984.  
</P>
</TEXT>
