<HEADLINE> ABB Agrees to Build Airports in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The infrastructure development
arm of Zurich-based ABB Asea Brown Boveri has signed an agreement
with the Egyptian Civil Aviation Authority for the construction
and operation of two airports in the Western Desert.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was signed on September 20, also provided
for ABB to develop tourism facilities around the airports in the
Farafra oasis, 460 kilometers southwest of Cairo, and Bahariya
oasis, about 350 kilometers southwest of the capital, the latest
issue of the Middle East Economic Digest (MEED) weekly reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will entail ABB signing a build-operate-transfer
(BOT) contract for the development of the airports and surrounding
areas, said the magazine, which focuses reports on the Middle East
economy and business.
</P>
<P>
ABB will construct and run the airports for 50 years before
handing them over to Egypt. It has nine months to prepare a
business plan for the project, after which final contracts are to
be signed.
</P>
<P>
The multinational corporation is estimated to invest some 110
million U.S. dollars in each airport over 10 years, and a further
280 million dollars in developing tourism facilities around the
airports.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government has offered incentives to lure foreign
investments in the country's infrastructural projects, including
airports, seaports and roads.
</P>
<P>
Besides the two aforesaid airports, Egypt will invite foreign
investors and the domestic private sector to build more than 10
airports in the early years of next century, which are mostly
tourist destinations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
