<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- A coalition crisis was defused Sunday night after the
religious party Shas reached an interim agreement with the
government that will allow salaries to be transferred to its
teachers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to lay out their differences in a
document and have given themselves 30 days to come up with a
permanent agreement. Shas had threatened to quit the government if
some 12 million shekels (about 2.8 million U.S. dollars) was not
transferred to its educational network.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- An inter-ministerial committee decided at a meeting
convened by Prime Minister Ehud Barak Sunday night to take a
series of limited steps aimed at tightening the supervision over
the Islamic Movement in Israel.
</P>
<P>
This followed the involvement of Israeli Arabs belonging to the
movement in two attempted car-bombing attacks in Haifa and
Tiberias, as well as the murder of a couple near the northern West
Bank, earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The General Security Service and police have expressed
"great disappointment" over the relatively moderate measures
decided by the government to restrict the Islamic Movement.
</P>
<P>
They were critical of the government for not implementing steps
designed to eradicate the movement's hostile activity, such as
closing down media that engage in incitement and shutting down
some of its institutions.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Barak will examine the new building permits issued by
Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
Peace Now said since the installation of the Barak government
at the beginning of July, the Housing Ministry has issued tenders
for the building of some 2,600 residential units in the West Bank
and Gaza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
