<HEADLINE> S.African Firm to Invest in Zambian Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government and South
Africa's Sun International have finally sealed the sale agreement
of Zambia's Mosi-O- Tunya Hotel Inter-Continental that will pave
way for the construction of three new hotels near the Victoria
Falls in Livingstone, the tourist capital of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Once operational, the new hotels will attract 130,000
international tourists, create 6,000 jobs and earn the country 40
million U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest investment under the accommodation sector to-date
is that of the Sun International, which is set to get off the
ground some time this month," Zambia's Acting Finance Minister
Vincent Malambo was quoted by Times of Zambia newspaper as saying
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Malambo was speaking in Lusaka at the weekend at a cultural
dinner hosted in preparation for the World Tourism Day which falls
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Malambo said over the past eight years, there had been a
measured improvement in the performance of the tourism sector in
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He said statistics indicated that there was a steady increase
in revenue generated from tourism while tourist arrivals,
investment pledges and job creation had increased.
</P>
<P>
"In 1994, tourist arrivals stood at 153,103. Last year there
were 362, 025. In 1994 revenue generated from tourists was 44.8
million dollars, last year it stood at 74.8 million dollars," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Malambo, who is Legal Affairs minister, said his ministry was
working out modalities that would deregulate the long legal
process in the industry to boost the tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
He said the newly launched national carrier, Zambian Airways,
would accord the industry a boost by bringing in tourists.
</P>
</TEXT>
