<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 07:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Poised to Follow More Assertive Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) is poised to follow a more aggressive foreign affairs policy
as it seeks to play a greater role within the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) and strengthen ties with the West.
</P>
<P>
With Lt. General Sheikh Mohammed Bin Zayed Al Nahyan, chief of
staff of the UAE Armed Forces, having a hand in the foreign
policy, the UAE is expected to make more assertive decisions,
according to a latest report of a Britain-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
The think tank on business and political affairs, the Economist
Intelligence Unit (EIU) said that the recent developments in the
Gulf have shown that the UAE is departing from traditional
discretion on its stance, the Gulf News daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
One notable example is the UAE's public objection to Saudi
Arabia's warmer relations with Iran, with which the UAE has a
territorial dispute.
</P>
<P>
Both the UAE and Saudi Arabia are members of the GCC, which
also includes Oman, Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain. Relations between
Saudi Arabia and Iran have been improving since Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami took office in 1997 and vowed to improve ties
with all countries, especially the Gulf Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia's overture toward Iran has angered the UAE because
it and Iran are locked in a dispute over the sovereignty of three
Gulf islands, the Abu Musa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the three strategic islets after Britain ended
its protectorate in 1975. So far, Iran only agrees to start
negotiation with the UAE over the Abu Musa.
</P>
<P>
"It will seek to play a greater role within the GCC by
increasing financial assistance to, and investment in, Oman and
Qatar in an effort to counter Saudi Arabia's influence in Bahrain
and Kuwait," analysts said in the EIU report.
</P>
<P>
"Fear of being dominated by Saudi Arabia and Iran, were U.S.
interests in the region to diminish, is pushing the UAE to seek
parity with Saudi Arabia in its regional influence," the report
added.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has recently settled a border dispute with Oman over
the Umm Al-Zamoul area with the promise of financial assistance.
The agreement led to Muscat's move to support the UAE to begin
developing oil reserves on the Abu Dhabi side of the border.
</P>
<P>
The border pact further gave Abu Dhabi the confidence to
express its anger over Saudi Arabia's move to resume harmonious
relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Oman reiterated its support to the UAE's claim to the islands,
without mentioning the prospects of improved ties with Iran, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Qatar was more cautious, but its foreign minister, Hamad Bin
Jassem Bin Jabr Al Thani, said that he could understand why the
UAE was displeased.
</P>
<P>
On the UAE's move to raise its international profile to reduce
the influence of potential aggressors, the country has been
involved recently in humanitarian efforts in Albania and has also
deployed peace keeping troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, said the report, the UAE keeps good
relations with Western powers like the U.S., France and Britain
by purchasing large amounts of weapons and maintaining military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"It will use its forthcoming naval expansion program to
broaden relations with any putative joint security apparatus in
Europe," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
