<HEADLINE> Jordan Promises to Reconsider Law on Honor Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Lower House Speaker
Abdul Hadi Majali has promised to take into consideration the
amending of the penal code which pardons or reduces penalties for
alleged honor killings.
</P>
<P>
The speaker said the House is ready to examine any ideas or
suggestions, hoping women groups would provide conclusion and
recommendations on the so-called honor killings, the semiofficial
Jordan Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks Sunday at the opening ceremony of a two-day
conference in Amman, which was entitled "Crimes of Honor - Latest
Developments" and organized by the Jordanian Women's Union.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that a Jordanian parliamentary leader
has promised to address the issue of honor killings, which claimed
dozens of lives of young women each year in the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Human rights and pressure groups in Amman have long campaigned
to remove the Article 340 in the penal code, which pardons or
reduces prison terms for those who kill their wives and female
relatives for actual or suspected illicit relationship with man.
</P>
<P>
A special committee under the Justice Ministry has decided to
eliminate Article 340, but the decision still needs the
endorsement of the lower and upper houses, then followed by a
Royal Decree.
</P>
<P>
An independent action committee have garnered more than 8,000
signatures during the first month of a nationwide campaign to
eliminate Article 340 and to stem alleged honor killings in the
kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
