<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Trainer's Edification Secret of Tightrope Walk King 's Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by sportwriter Wang Zijiang
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Every time he comes off the
high wire, Adili, the "tightrope walk king", always recalls his
late trainer Liu Fusheng.
</P>
<P>
"Right before he passed away five years ago, Liu told me that I
should aim high and fly. I will never let him down," said Adili,
28, an member of the Uygur minority nationality in Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region in northwestern China.
</P>
<P>
Adili, who is participating in the on-going China's National
Games for the Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities in
Beijing, has been listed as one of the world's most successful
tightrope walkers.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old usually tiptoes along an angled cable leading
to a tight wire dangling some 20 meters above the ground and
performs such daredevil routines as forward and backward steps,
walk blindfolded, somersaults, sit-up, stand upside down on head
top and jumps.
</P>
<P>
Adili established his world-wide fame in June 1997 when he
performed a record-setting walk along a wire stretched across
China's longest river the Yangtze, in 13 minutes and 48 seconds.
He completed the performance on the 640.75-meter steel wire
dangling 375 meters above the flushing water. It broke the
previous Guinness world record of 53 minutes and 10 seconds set at
the same site by Canadian tightrope walker Jay Cochraine in
October of 1995.
</P>
<P>
A seventh-generation member of Xinjiang's famed professional
Dawazi (tightrope walkers) family, Adili said he could not have
achieved such a stunning success without the help of his trainer,
although he could make steps on the tightrope ever since he was
five.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Han nationality himself, Liu, an acrobatic
coach in his hometown Yingjisha County of Xinjiang is a close
friend of Adili's father.
</P>
<P>
Adili's father died in 1976, when his son was only five.
Fearing his family's traditional stun skills would get lost, he
asked Liu, before his death, to look after his son and continue to
teach him the skills.
</P>
<P>
"My trainer took me a son of his own," Adili recalled. "He
taught me all about Dawazi, and told me how to be a man. Without
him, I would have never flown up in the air," Adili said.
</P>
<P>
Liu died five years ago.
</P>
<P>
In an accident caused by a snapped wire years ago in Shanghai,
Adili fell 15 meters to the ground, breaking a collarbone, pubic
bones and several ribs and injuring his kidney.
</P>
<P>
As nobody thought he would be able to perform again on the
tightrope, Adili almost gave up his hope. It was Liu's
encouragement that helped him restore the confidence. "Once I
thought of my trainer's words, I told myself that I should not
flinch." He managed to resume performing the stunt just after
sixth months' rest.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrating Dawazi skills in the National Games for
Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities only to the second
time, Adili wished liu's family members in Xinjiang would be
watching him perform through TV screen.
</P>
<P>
"I will keep on flying in the future," he said. "I will never
disappoint them," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
