<HEADLINE> Chinese Canadians Celebrate National Day of People's Republic of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Chinese Canadians
paraded in downtown streets Sunday in celebration of the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Led by a band and traditional Chinese dragon and lion dances
and waving national flags of China and Canada, the paraders walked
from Donald Park to the city hall, where a flag-raising ceremony
was held.
</P>
<P>
When the five-starred national red flag of China was being
hoisted and the Chinese national anthem played, the participants,
including several Canadian parliament members and Jim Watson,
Mayor of Ottawa, saluted.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Chinese Ambassador Mei Ping hailed the great
achievements China has gained in the past 50 years and expressed
hope for better strategic partnership between China and Canada.
</P>
<P>
In their congratulatory speeches, Canadian officials said that
bilateral ties have developed in recent years and stressed the
need for furthering friendship in the new century.
</P>
<P>
In Montreal, more than 1,000 members of the local Chinese
community participated in a flag-raising ceremony and paraded in
China Town on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Massive celebrations are being planned in Vancouver and Toronto,
where more than 100 Chinese organizations are preparing activities,
including a drum dance parade and a photo exhibition. 
</P>
