<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Foreign Direct Investment Declines in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct
investment (FDI) inflows to Malaysia declined by 27 percent in
1998 over the previous year, according to World Investment Report
1999 released by the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development
(UNCTAD) office here Monday.
</P>
<P>
FDI inflows to Malaysia in 1998 amounted to 3.7 billion U.S.
dollars against 5.1 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, the figures
show.
</P>
<P>
However, the value of FDI in the manufacturing sector, the
driving force of the country's economy, approved, registered a 14
percent increase in 1998 when projects worth 3.43 billion U.S.
dollars were approved against 3 billion U.S. dollars approved in
1997.
</P>
<P>
FDI is defined as a long-term investment into all sectors of
economy excluding portfolio funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
