<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Slams U.S. Report on Religious Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) has condemned the United States for its
groundless slandering of the DPRK on religious freedom, press
reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a "1999 annual report on international religious freedom"
published on September 9, the United States charged that religious
freedom in the DPRK is not guaranteed and harsh penalties are
inflicted on those taking part in religious activities.
</P>
<P>
The official Korean Central News Agency quoted a Foreign
Ministry spokesman as warning on Sunday that if the United States
continues to put pressure on the DPRK over the "religious problem"
based on false data, it would jeopardize the narrowly progressed
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have improved slightly as
the United States announced recently to ease economic sanctions
against the DPRK after their talks in Germany earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman denounced the U.S. religion report as "another
broad attempt to interfere in others' internal affairs in
violation of basic international norms," just like its annual
slanderous report on human rights conditions in other countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted the move could not work on anyone and will only invite
ridicule and rejection.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that in his country religious belief and
freedom of people are perfectly ensured by the constitution, and
that believers can go in for religious activities at their will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
