<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Navy Repulses Rebels' Attack on Chinese Cargo Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's navy over the
weekend repulsed a Tamil rebels' attack on a Chinese cargo ship
off the northeastern coast of the country, security sources said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
They said the ship carrying fertilizer was on its way to South
India's Madras when it was fired upon by Tamil rebels Saturday
night about 50 miles east of Mullaitivu, the stronghold of Tamil
rebels, 280 kilometers northeast of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The stern of the cargo ship was badly damaged from a rocket
propelled grenade from a boat of Tamil rebels of Liberation Tigers
of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
About 15 Navy fast attack craft patrolling the seas had come to
the rescue of the cargo ship and engaged the LTTE rebels in a
fierce high sea battle.
</P>
<P>
During the nine-hour battle lasting till four on Sunday
morning, the navy beat back the attack of 12 LTTE's water jet
boats, destroying four of them, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
They said the cargo ship with 34 people aboard was later towed
into Trincomalee port, about 250 kilometers northeast of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
One person was injured in the attack.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the LTTE rebels had been attempting to
frighten civilian ships and cargo ships away from Sri Lankan
shores by launching terrorist attacks, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a 16-year-old war against
the government to demand an independent homeland for minority
Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Pledges to Enhance Debt Relief Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and World Bank announced here Sunday an enhanced debt
relief initiative to help the poorest countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
At the first-ever joint meeting of policy setting committees,
the two agencies pledged to support "deeper, broader and faster
debt relief" for the poor countries and strengthen the link
between debt relief and poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The new coordinated effort will provide a debt relief of 100
billion U.S. dollars to 36 of the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
Some requirements are erased to allow three-fourths of the
eligible countries, many in sub-Saharan Africa, into the debt
relief program by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
In September 1996, the IMF and World Bank launched an
Initiative for the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) to cut
some 70 billion dollars in nominal terms off the 214 billion
dollar debt burden of the world's 40 poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
However, because of strict performance standards, so far only
four countries -- Uganda, Bolivia, Guyana and Mozambique -- have
received relief under the HIPC.
</P>
<P>
The new debt relief initiative, to be financed in part by
revaluing 14 million ounces of the IMF's gold reserves at market
prices, would provide 50 billion dollars for the HIPC debt relief
program.
</P>
<P>
Valued in its accounts at less than 50 U.S. dollars an ounce,
the IMF's gold will be sold for cash at the current market price,
which is above 260 dollars, thus enabling the IMF to spend the
difference.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal was strongly protested in gold producer
countries, some of which are among the poorest that the HIPC
program was supposed to help. They fear such a sale would cause a
price collapse and throw thousands of people out of work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Continues to Rise in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- For the first time in 10
weeks, the inflation rate rose past the two percent mark to 2.02
percent for the week ending September 11, due to an increase in
the prices of primary articles.
</P>
<P>
According to the Reserve Bank of India, during the week, the
annual rate of inflation rose by 0.08 percentage points to 2.02
percent from 1.94 percent in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate was much higher at 8.36 percent during the
corresponding week last year.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate is expected to rise in the coming months
with a new government likely to effect a hike in oil prices to
bridge the gap between the rising international prices and the
administered rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
