<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caffeine Declared Restricted Product in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Office of the
Narcotics Control Board has declared caffeine to be a restricted
substance in 32 districts of six northern provinces bordering
Myanmar and Laos, the Nation reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following the growing popularity of
caffeine as an ingredient in amphetamine tablets, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Caffeine has been mixed with other ingredients to help reduce
production costs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, figures from the Customs Department showed that some
37 tons of caffeine had been imported to Thailand between January
and March this year.
</P>
<P>
About 30 tons went to northern provinces for re-export to
Myanmar, some border areas of which house plants making
amphetamine tablets for sale in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
