<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Seek Evidence for Evolution of Chinese Civilization ( 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Widely recognized nowadays,
the fact that the Chinese civilization has a 5,000 year history
was doubted and challenged half a century ago. Finding evidence
for this conclusion, therefore, has become a common goal pursued
by Chinese archeologists during the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Numerous archeological finds since the founding of New China
have helped scholars to piece together the course of development
of Chinese civilization. The central China province of Henan made
particularly important contributions with its rich cultural
heritage.
</P>
<P>
Experts agree that excavations of the five historical sites in
Henan, and research of findings unearthed at these sites, provide
sound evidence for establishing the existence of the Xia (about
2100 -- 1600 B.C.) and Shang (1600 -- 1100 BC) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
"All these heritages, except the Yin site in Anyang, were
discovered during the past 50 years," according to An Jinhuai, a
78-year-old veteran archeologist who has devoted the past 50 years
to searching for and excavating the cultural heritage sites in
Henan.
</P>
<P>
Documents show that most areas of Henan Province fall into
centers of the Xia and Shang dynasties. Archeologists have
therefore focused their research on Xia and Shang cultures with
the findings in the province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists of New China had their first significant finds in
the spring of 1951, when a Shang Dynasty site was unearthed in
Zhengzhou, capital of Henan. Four years later, the remains of a
Shang city were excavated at the site, which is the largest to be
found so far. The Shang city in Zhengzhou is believed to be more
ancient than the Shang city in Anyang, which was excavated in 1928.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Seek Evidence for Evolution of Chinese Civilization ( 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the discovery of another Shang city in Yanshi in 1983,
Chinese archeologists were able to patch a basic framework for the
history of the Shang Dynasty. They unanimously held that the
ancient city in Yanshi was built even earlier than the Shang city
in Zhengzhou, and could be a landmark dividing the culture of the
Xia Dynasty from the Shang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Another important contribution from Henan has been the
archeological exploration of Xia culture. An ancient city was
unearthed in 1983 in Dengfeng, which was established as the first
capital city of the Xia Dynasty, thereby bringing the history of
Chinese cities to an even earlier date of between 2300 BC and 2200
BC.
</P>
<P>
"More than 20 ancient dynasties located their capitals in Henan,
which left the province rich in the vestiges of ancient
civilization," said Chang Jianchuan, director of the Henan
Provincial Bureau of Cultural Relics. "But the most significant
archeological findings are related to the cultures of the Xia and
Shang dynasties."
</P>
<P>
Chang's view was echoed by Zhang Guangzhi, a Chinese-American
scholar, "The science of archeology has made many spectacular
finds; our top finding has been the culture of the Xia, Shang and
Zhou dynasties."
</P>
<P>
"Whereas fifty years ago we didn't know how or where the
history of China began, we know it now," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
