<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transportation Greatly Improved in Qinghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Fan Changjiang, a pioneer
Chinese journalist, rode a horse through Qinghai Province in
northwest China, and depicted the poverty in the province in his
book "Northwest Corner of China."
</P>
<P>
That was before the founding of New China in 1949. Now, a
modern transportation network has been created in Qinghai.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-seven flights now take off every week from the Xining
airport in the provincial capital bound for other parts of the
country, and more than 20,000 travelers came to Qinghai by air in
August alone.
</P>
<P>
Tracks have been laid to Golmud as part of the railway line
from Qinghai to Tibet. Golmud, once a small village, now handles
90 percent of the materials and 80 percent of the passengers
heading for Tibet, making it a hot tourist city.
</P>
<P>
Upgrading of the Xining-Lhasa Highway, the main highway passage
leading to Tibet, was recently completed, and cars can now travel
at speeds of up to 80 kilometers per hour on the highway, twice
the original speed.
</P>
<P>
According to a local source, nearly all the towns and townships
in Qinghai now have access to highways.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
