<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Today's Life of Those Guarding Genghis Khan's Mausoleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-three-year-old Yang
Qingke is a guard at Genghis Khan's Mausoleum in China's Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region, but he works as a tour guide on the
side.
</P>
<P>
He gets more than 400 yuan (48 U.S. dollars) monthly from his
guard work and his family also has more than 100 sheep and a total
annual income of more than 10,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
His life did not get this way until the chaotic "Cultural
Revolution" came to an end in 1976. The Central Government then
allocated funds to rebuild the mausoleum which had been severely
damaged during that period and gave him money to guard it and some
land for his livestock.
</P>
<P>
Genghis Khan (1162-1227) died at the age of 66 in what is today
Gansu Province, when he attacked the Xixia Kingdom to try to unify
the country. His remains were taken to the Ejin Horo Banner on the
Ordos Highlands in Inner Mongolia and buried there. Five hundred
families were chosen to protect the mausoleum. Yang comes from one
of those families.
</P>
<P>
Guards moved Genghis Khan's remains to Qinghai Province when
Japanese troops invaded China in 1937 and the mausoleum was left
behind. The remains did not return to the region until the
founding of New China in 1949. The mausoleum was rebuilt as 3
connected palaces and Yang Qingke became the 38th generation to
take care of the mausoleum.
</P>
<P>
Wang Dao'er, the head of the mausoleum's Administrative Bureau,
says that the guards used to live near the mausoleum and all
looked after it and prepared memorial ceremonies every March 21 of
the lunar calendar. Now, only 54 people guard it and hold memorial
services and they serve as tour guides on the side.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1,000 members of the 500 families living
elsewhere in the Ordos Highlands and more than 2,000 living near
the mausoleum and farming, doing business, or working for the
local government. Many younger members have their own hotels,
restaurants, or shops near the scenic spot and provide various
services for tourists and carry on the folk tradition on wedding
days and for ceremonies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
