<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Size of Thai Mission to East Timor to Be Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The size of the Thai force
going to East Timor on a peacekeeping mission may be reduced to
about 1,100 from 1,778 under the original plan, Bangkok Post
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chokchai Hongthong, the Thai armed forces chief of staff, was
quoted as saying on Sunday that the cut is being made at the
request of Prime Minister and Defense Minister Chuan Leekpai.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces have agreed to propose sending either 1,100
men, 1,200 or 1,400 men, Chokchai said. The prime minister is
expected to choose the first figure, he added.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the Thai troops are from the Rapid Deployment
Force of the 3rd Battalion of the 31st Infantry Regiment,
according to Chokchai.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 33 Thai soldiers left for Darwin of
Australia to join an advance multinational peacekeeping force in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The second batch of 100 soldiers will leave for Darwin before
October 1. They will later proceed to Bakao in East Timor, and the
main part of the Thai force will leave for the territory on
October 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
