<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quayle Quits U.S. Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Vice President
Dan Quayle has decided to drop out of the Republican presidential
race, the Associated Press said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Quayle made the decision after determining that he cannot
compete with Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush
in fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
Quayle is expected to announce his intentions at a news
conference Monday in Phoenix, Arizona. His departure left eight
major candidates in the Republican field for presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
Quayle's aides said the former vice president decided to quit
this weekend, after consulting with his wife, Marilyn, and
campaign manager Kyle McSlarrow.
</P>
<P>
The former vice president is not able to raise enough money to
compete deep into the primary season with Texas Governor George W.
Bush, who has raised more than 50 million dollars, five times that
of his nearest challenger. Quayle has been running a debt since
early in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Representative John Kasich of Ohio, former Tennessee Governor
Lamar Alexander and Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire, dropped
out of the Republican primary contest earlier this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
