<DOCNO> XIE19990927.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Karelin Wins His Ninth World Champion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Alexander Karelin of Russia
continued his domination by winning his ninth world title Sunday,
the final day of the Greco-Roman Wrestling World Championships.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old Karelin, who has never lost an international
match, beat Hector Milian of Cuba 3-0 for the 130-kilo title. But
the three-time Olympic gold medalist didn't have an easy time
doing it, trying in vain several times to flip his opponent.
</P>
<P>
The Russian team led the competition with 40 points and
qualifying five for the 2000 Sydney Olympics. Both Cuba, second
with 38 points, and South Korea, third with 32 points, followed
with four each.
</P>
<P>
In other contests Sunday, Luis Mendez of Cuba went into extra
time to win the 85-kilo gold medal, beating Thomas Zander of
Germany, 5-1.
</P>
<P>
Behrouz Jamshidi of Iran finished in third place, scoring a 3-1
victory over Raatbek Sanatbaev of Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
At 69 kilos, Son Sang-pil of South Korea used a pair a small
flips to recapture his world title, topping Russia's Alexander
Tretiakov, 4-0, to win the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Son won the world championship in 1997, again beating Tretiakov,
but came in third place in 1998. Tretiakov took the title that
year.
</P>
<P>
Vladzimir Kapytav of Belarus won the bronze medal on technical
points, 3-1, as his bout with Csaba Hirbik of Hungary finished in
a 4-4 tie.
</P>
<P>
Kim In-sub of South Korea needed all nine minutes (six minutes
of regulation and three minutes of extra time), but he was able to
outlast Yury Melnichenko of Kazakhstan, 2-0, for the gold medal in
the 58 kg category.
</P>
<P>
Kim also won the 1998 world championship while Melnichenko won
the world title in 1994 and 1997 and a gold medal in the 1996
Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Armen Nazarian of Bulgaria took the bronze medal, beating Ihar
Piatrenka of Belarus, 6-0.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
