<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Thai Commercial Banks Cut Deposit Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok Bank, the country's largest commercial bank, cut its
annual interest rates for savings account to 3.5 percent from 3.75
percent and its prime lending rate to 8.5 percent from 8.75
percent.
</P>
<P>
Thai Farmers Bank, Bangkok Bank's major competitor, announced a
cut of deposit rates and minimum lending rates on all accounts
equal the rates of the latter, except the rates for 24-month fixed
accounts which were left unchanged at five percent a year.
</P>
<P>
State-owned Krung Thai Bank cut its deposit rates for 12-month
fixed account to 4.75 percent from five percent, but leaving the
rates for other savings and fixed accounts and lending rates
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Ayudhya also whittled down its deposit rates for
12-month fixed account to 4.75 percent from five percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
