<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wimbledon Hoping for Ref Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Wimbledon manager Egil Olsen
is hoping video evidence to prove John Hartson is innocent after
he was sent off for using his elbow on Spurs defender Luke Young.
</P>
<P>
Hartson picked up a second yellow card after 79 minutes of the
1-1 draw at Selhurst Park and now faces a one-match ban.
</P>
<P>
But Olsen branded the incident, which was spotted by the
referee's assistant, as "a wrong decision" and will ask referee
Graham Poll to look at the tape and maybe change his mind.
</P>
<P>
"I have watched it again on TV and it is a wrong decision,"
said Olsen. "Everybody in the team thinks it was a wrong decision.
</P>
<P>
"John did not use his elbow and I cannot see anything wrong,
the tapes don't lie. You cannot jump with your arms by your sides
but John did not use his elbow.
</P>
<P>
"Players make mistakes and so do referees, and John should not
be banned for this. The linesman was further away from the
incident than the referee. I wonder if people in this country don'
t like him."
</P>
<P>
Olsen was unaware that it is possible to appeal against such
decisions and ask for the referee to view the incident again.
</P>
<P>
But he is likely to take that course of action after having it
explained to him by the media.
</P>
<P>
He said: "In Norway, it is not possible, but now you have told
me this I shall discuss it with the people around me. If the
referee is prepared to change his mind that will be good of him."
</P>
<P>
Amazingly, since working with Hartson, Olsen believes the big
Welsh striker needs to be more aggressive. He said: "I like John
as a person and a player but he can improve. He is very soft and
can be more aggressive." 
</P>
</TEXT>
